[{"id":"VR834533","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an electric field labeled vector E. The field is represented by 4 columns of arrows in 3 rows. The first column of arrows are short, with the arrows in the top and bottom rows pointing downward and to the right and upward and to the right respectively, and the middle column pointing horizontally to the right. Moving from left to right, each column of arrows becomes longer, and the top and bottom arrows point more towards the middle row of arrows. Point A is indicated between the first and second columns along the middle row. Point B is indicated between the third and fourth columns along the middle row.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834533.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An electric field in a region of space has a nonuniform magnitude, as depicted by the electric field map in the figure. A positive point charge (not shown) already in motion at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span>, moves due to the field alone to Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>. As the point charge moves from Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> to Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>, its kinetic energy increases by an amount <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta K\"><math alttext=\"delta K\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>K</mi></math></span></span>, while the electric potential energy of the point charge-field system decreases by an amount <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the absolute value of delta U\"><math alttext=\"the absolute value of delta U\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>|</mo><mtext>Δ</mtext><mi>U</mi><mo>|</mo></math></span></span>. Are <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta K\"><math alttext=\"delta K\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>K</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the absolute value of delta U\"><math alttext=\"the absolute value of delta U\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>|</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>U</mi><mo>|</mo></math></span></span> equal to one another? What evidence or reasoning supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR834533_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. The total energy of the system remains constant in the absence of external forces.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. The point charge’s speed increases as it moves from Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> to Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. The point charge is already moving at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span>, rather than starting from rest.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. The electric field magnitude changes between points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>, rather than being uniform.</p>"],"answer":0}]